Title : Kal Rudman
Text : {{Multiple issues|
{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}
{{more footnotes|date=April 2017}}
}}

'''Solomon "Kal" Rudman''' is an American former [[disc jockey]], long-time publisher of the music industry magazine "Friday Morning Quarterback," <ref> Andy Gotlieb. "Man of Many Hats Focuses Today on Philanthropy." ''Jewish Exponent'', August 10, 2016. [http://jewishexponent.com/2016/08/10/man-of-many-hats-focuses-today-on-philanthropy/] </ref> and a [[philanthropist]]. He founded the [[Kal and Lucille Rudman Foundation]] with his wife.

==Early life and education==
Born in Philadelphia, Rudman attended Ferguson School, then graduated from [[Central High School (Philadelphia)|Central High School]] with a strong interest in radio. He received a bachelor's degree in education from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1951, and working as a [[Special education in the United States|special education]] teacher.

==Career==
He later became a [[Top 40]] disc jockey at [[WCAM]] in [[Camden, New Jersey]], and later [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] magazine's first [[R&B]] editor.

In 1968, out of his basement, he began publishing ''Friday Morning Quarterback'', a [[music industry]] [[trade magazine]]. He said in an interview with the ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' in 1994 that he was the first to spot [[Judy Collins]]' "Send in the Clowns," [[Hall and Oates]]' "She's Gone," and [[Kenny Rogers]]' "Lucille" as hits.

Rudman appeared on ''[[The Merv Griffin Show]]'' more than 30 times, was a music-expert regular on the ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today Show]]'', and was known as "Killer Kal" for his work as an announcer for the [[World Wrestling Federation]].

He advised [[Bruce Springsteen]] on how to make his music more popular with females. "Hungry Heart" on ''The River'' album, released in 1980. "Kal explained to me that Top 40 radio is mainly listened to by girls and that my female demographic was low," Springsteen said in an interview at the time.<ref>http://www.southjerseymagazine.com/articles/?articleid=573</ref>

His flagship trade publication, among six, is ''Friday Morning Quarterback ([[FMQB]])'', a music industry trade magazine. ''Forbes'' called Rudman one of the major influences in the leisure and entertainment industry in the United States.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1981/07/26/kal-rudman-prophet-of-pop/df755c12-8866-4040-903b-aacf125efda8/</ref>

Rudman is still active in radio. He is a weekly guest on ''Bob Pantano's Dance Party'' on [[WOGL]] in Philadelphia.

===WWF (1977-1989)===
Rudman mostly called the monthly action for [[PRISM (TV network)|PRISM]] for the [[WWE|WWF]]'s arena shows that took place at the [[Philadelphia Spectrum]]. Rudman was often paired with either Dick Graham or [[Gorilla Monsoon]]. Rudman earned the nickname "Killer Kal" while interviewing [[Hulk Hogan]]. Sometimes he would also appear for the WWF's monthly [[Madison Square Garden]] shows and as a fill-in interviewer on ''[[WWF Championship Wrestling]]''. After the WWF stopped airing the shows in the Spectrum on PRISM in 1989, Rudman no longer contributed for the WWF. Rudman helped [[Vince McMahon]] gain contacts in the entertainment world during McMahon's [[1980s wrestling boom|national expansion in the Rock 'n' Wrestling era]].

==Honors and awards==

Rudman has been awarded honorary doctorates from [[Drexel University]], the [[University of the Arts (Philadelphia)|University of the Arts]], and [[Holy Family University]]. He has been selected to the Philadelphia Broadcast Pioneers Hall of Fame,<ref>http://www.broadcastpioneers.com/bp1/kalrudman.html</ref> and has been named that group's "Person of the Year";  “Man of the Year” by the Black Music Association; “Community Philanthropist of the Year” by Community College of Philadelphia; as well as receiving a plaque on the Music Legends Walk of Fame in Philadelphia. He is also an Honorary Philadelphia Fire Commissioner and Honorary Deputy Police Commissioner.

==Personal life==
Rudman, and his wife Lucille, have been residents of [[Cherry Hill, New Jersey]].<ref>Riordan, Kevin. [https://web.archive.org/web/20161002130211/http://articles.philly.com/2016-03-07/news/71250037_1_kal-rudman-rudman-institute-friday-morning-quarterback "Kal Rudman, music maven, philanthropist (and legend)"], ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', March 7, 2016, backed up by the [[Internet Archive]] as of October 2, 2016. Accessed January 3, 2018. "He and I are chatting in the gracious Cherry Hill home he shares with Lucille, his wife of 58 years."</ref>

